Title

CIVILIZATION CLOTHING SYSTEMS: A SEMIOTIC, TECHNOLOGICAL, AND ADAPTIVE FRAMEWORK FROM EARTH TO MARS

Towards a Unified Theory of Wearable Interfaces – From Neolithic Weaves to Adaptive Exoskins

Author

Ouadi Maakoul


Abstract

Clothing is humanity‘s most ancient and persistent artifact, operating simultaneously as physical protection, social encoding, and symbolic communication. Yet existing scholarship treats these dimensions separately: semiotics focuses on clothing as linguistic code, anthropology examines its social life, and engineering reduces it to functional layers. This fragmentation becomes critical as humanity prepares for long‑duration Mars missions, where clothing must transform from passive protection into active life support, wearable computer, identity system, and biological regulator.

This thesis develops an integrated framework—the Adaptive Interface System (AIS) —that models clothing as emerging from the interaction of four design drivers: environmental constraints, material technologies, socio‑political structures, and philosophical systems. Using grounded theory analysis of archaeological and ethnographic textile traditions (Neolithic Europe, Andean cultures, Islamic geometric patterns, African Kente cloth), we derive and empirically validate a five‑category taxonomy of textile pattern systems: geometric, bio‑morphic, mytho‑symbolic, socio‑encoded, and abstract semantic. Theoretical sampling on Japanese Edo‑period kimono confirms the taxonomy‘s predictive power.

Extending the AIS framework to post‑Earth environments, we propose a new class of garments—Adaptive Exoskin Systems (AES) —designed for a first‑generation Mars surface habitat (2035–2045). The AES architecture integrates three functional layers (inner bio‑layer, middle adaptive layer, outer shield layer) with four pattern innovations: (1) functional patterning (thermal, oxygen, radiation mapping), (2) data‑driven aesthetics (real‑time dashboard using pixel‑addressable electroluminochromic fibers), (3) identity encoding (mission role, cultural continuity, psychological state signaling), and (4) algorithmic generation via a Generative Pattern Engine (GPE) trained on terrestrial pattern taxonomies. We introduce three novel sub‑systems grounded in recent research: chrono‑semiotic circadian patterning (wavelength shifts to regulate melatonin over the 24.6‑hour Martian sol), phyllotaxis cooling channel architecture (biomimetic heat distribution based on the golden angle), and a semiotics of disassembly (visual grammar for in‑situ repair). Feasibility assessment against NASA’s Z‑2, Digital Thread, and ExoSkin prototypes shows most AES components at TRL 5‑6.

The thesis makes three original contributions: (1) the first empirically validated, systems‑based taxonomy of clothing pattern systems across civilizations, (2) a unified AIS model bridging material and semiotic analyses, and (3) a prototype‑informed design architecture for Martian clothing that treats garments as wearable habitat, computer, identity system, and biological regulator simultaneously. Finally, we show that Mars design principles—multi‑layer functional integration, digital manufacturing, repairability, algorithmic customization—offer heuristics for transitioning Earth’s fashion industry from linear to circular systems.

Keywords: clothing semiotics, textile pattern systems, design drivers, Mars habitation, adaptive exoskins, grounded theory, human‑environment interaction, chrono‑semiotics, generative pattern engine, phyllotaxis cooling, semiotics of disassembly

