Appendix C: Mathematical Derivations for AES Sub‑Systems

C.1 Phyllotaxis Cooling Channel Equations

Golden angle derivation:

The golden angle φ is derived from the golden ratio Φ = (1 + √5)/2 ≈ 1.618034.

φ = 360° × (1 − 1/Φ) = 360° × (1 − 0.618034) = 360° × 0.381966 = 137.5078° ≈ 137.5°

In radians: φ = 2π × (1 − 1/Φ) = 2π × 0.381966 = 2.39996 rad

Channel coordinates:

For n = 0, 1, 2, …, N (channel index):

θₙ = n × φ (mod 360°)

rₙ = c × √n

where:

· c = scaling constant determined by suit geometry and thermal load
· c = √(A / (π × N)) for uniform coverage over surface area A

Channel depth scaling:

Local channel depth d(θ, r) proportional to predicted heat flux Q(θ, r):

d(θ, r) = dₘᵢₙ + (dₘₐₓ − dₘᵢₙ) × (Q(θ, r) − Qₘᵢₙ) / (Qₘₐₓ − Qₘᵢₙ)

where Q(θ, r) is obtained from Digital Twin thermal simulation.

Hydraulic diameter for microchannel:

Dₕ = 4 × (width × depth) / (2 × (width + depth))

For typical AES parameters: width = 500 μm, depth = 200–500 μm → Dₕ ≈ 267–333 μm.

Reynolds number (laminar flow assumption):

Re = ρ × v × Dₕ / μ

where ρ = fluid density (water/glycol mixture ~ 1050 kg/m³), v = flow velocity (~0.1 m/s), μ = dynamic viscosity (~0.002 Pa·s). Re ≈ 14–17 (well within laminar range, Re < 2000).

C.2 Chrono‑Semiotic Circadian Patterning: Wavelength and Melatonin Suppression

Melatonin suppression action spectrum (λ, nm):

Based on the non‑image forming visual system sensitivity (melanopsin peak at ~480 nm).

Relative suppression S(λ) = 1 / (1 + exp(−k(λ − λ₀)))

where λ₀ = 480 nm, k = 0.1 nm⁻¹ (sigmoidal fit to published action spectra).

Wavelength schedule over Martian sol (24.6 hours):

Sol Phase Time (hours) Target λ (nm) Function
Wake transition 0.0 – 0.5 631 (red) Minimal suppression, gradual transition
Morning 0.5 – 2.0 590–550 (amber to green) Gradual shift
Mid‑sol alertness 2.0 – 18.0 500–550 (green to white) Maintain alertness
Pre‑sleep transition 18.0 – 21.0 480–460 (blue) Suppress melatonin, reset circadian pacemaker
Wind‑down 21.0 – 23.0 500–550 (green) Reduce suppression
Sleep preparation 23.0 – 24.6 631 (dim red) Allow melatonin recovery

Light intensity scaling:

Irradiance E (μW/cm²) required for 50% melatonin suppression at λ = 480 nm: E₅₀ ≈ 2.5 μW/cm² (corneal). For AES electroluminochromic fibers: target output 5–10 μW/cm² at suit surface (accounting for attenuation through helmet visor).

C.3 Ablative Radiation Dosimetry: Pattern Erosion Model

Cumulative radiation dose D(t) = ∫ R(t) dt

where R(t) = instantaneous dose rate (mGy/day) from GCR and SPE.

Pattern element erosion function:

Intensity I(x,y,t) = I₀(x,y) × exp(−α × D(t))

where α = erosion coefficient (material‑specific, determined empirically).

Warning threshold:

When I(x,y,t) falls below I_threshold (e.g., 20% of I₀), pattern element is considered “erased” and outer layer replacement is indicated.

Example for polycarbonate outer layer (α ≈ 0.15 per 100 mGy):

Dose (mGy) Remaining Intensity (%) Visual Indication
0 100 Full pattern
100 86 Slight fading
300 64 Noticeable fading
500 47 Warning pattern half‑erased
800 30 Critical — replace soon
1000 22 Replacement required

C.4 Generative Pattern Engine: Conditional GAN Architecture

Generator G(z | c): Maps latent vector z ~ N(0,1) and condition vector c to pattern image I.

Discriminator D(I | c): Distinguishes real pattern (from training set) from generated pattern, conditioned on c.

Condition vector c encoding (five‑category taxonomy):

c = [cat_geometric, cat_biomorphic, cat_mythosymbolic, cat_socioencoded, cat_abstractsemantic]

where each category is a one‑hot encoded dimension, plus continuous parameters for color palette (RGB weights), symmetry group (one‑hot of 17 wallpaper groups), and fractal dimension target.

Loss function:

L = min_G max_D [ E[log D(I_real|c)] + E[log(1 − D(G(z|c)|c))] + λ × L_perceptual ]

where L_perceptual = VGG‑based perceptual loss to ensure pattern coherence.

Training dataset: Curated database of 50,000 textile pattern images from museum collections, categorized by the five‑category taxonomy with expert validation.

